<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-366-250  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 366 250.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  June 12 1989 v216 n24 p38(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber to the home? A lot will depend on how you splice it. (fiberoptics and telecommunications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patterson, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Debate continues about the best architecture for deploying fiberoptics to the home.andP;  Almost everyone agrees that telephonecompanies will deploy residential fiber, so that debate focuses onregulatory, technological and economic issues.andP;  Fundamentalinstallation issues, however, are also important, and debateshould take deployment and maintenance costs into account.andP;  Marketresearch by 3M TeleComm Products Div indicates bringing fiber toAmerica's homes requires eight times more fiber than used for thenation's long-haul facilities, and the number of splices per mileof distribution fiber will be about 20 times greater than per mileof long-haul fiber.andP;  Fiber to homes will require many splices andno regenerators.andP;  Costs will be significant.andP;  Whatever lowersthese costs will make fiber more attractive economically,hastening its deployment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   3M Co. TeleComm Products Div. (research).andO;Topic:     Fiber opticsTelephone companiesTelephone systemsGovernment RegulationSocial IssuesSystem Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   How the splice works. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>